[Student "W"]
{[showcards S:H2]

You are South. The bidding has been as shown.

Your lead of the \CJ was won by East with the \CA. East then played the \H2 and you must decide whether to split your honors.

Play the \H4, do not split your Honors.

East's bidding showed at least 5 \Hs, so assuming he holds both the \H A Q, it would be silly for him to finesse the \H9 on the first trump play.

As it turns out, when you play low East calls for dummy's \HK, North's \HQ falls and you now have 2 trump tricks. If you had played the \H10 you would have tossed away the setting trick.}
[Play "W"]CJ

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "5"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "S:A5.AT975.AQJ.J86 JT64.K.7642.KQ75 K7.J8632.K53.T42 Q9832.Q4.T98.A93"]
[Declarer "S"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "S"]
1H pass 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 5, chOption: S, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:2, nBasis: 2, nRot: 0, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "0aebf656f7f2bc3bec156d439d12678e2a77a91b7ae76c6d7d674ad85dd0e750"]
[Category "Defense"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "defense/second_hand_play"]
[Student "E"]
{[showcards N:HJ]

You are East. The bidding has been as shown.

Partner led the \CK, and you played the \C9 to encourage him. He continued with the \CQ, then a small card to your \CA. You then exit with the \D10, taken by dummy's \DK.

Declarer then calls for the \HJ. Do you cover with your \HQ or not?

Play the \H4.

North has 5 \Hs and South must have at least 5. The reason you cover an Honor is that you hope to establish a lower card in either your hand or partner's hand. But your partner has one \H at the most so there is no hope of establishment.

Now that you have looked at the hands aren't you glad you didn't cover?}
[Play "W"]CK

